Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
editSelect(25.10)                                            editSelect(25.10)

Name
       editSelect - Selects wires and vias using the specified parameters

Syntax
       editSelect

       [-help]

       [-area {<x1> <y1> <x2> <y2>}]

       [-direction {H | V | 45 | 135}]

       [-floating_via]

       [-layer <list_of_layers>]

       [-nets <net>*]

       [-physical_pin_only]

       [-regular_wire_with_drc]

       [-shape {RING STRIPE FOLLOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE PADRING

                BLOCKRING FILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC DRCFILL None}]

       [-shield]

       [-shield_only]

       [-status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN}]

       [-subclass <sublass_name>]

       [-type {Regular Special Patch}]

       [-use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}]

       [-via_cell <cell_name_list>]

       [-with_edit_flag {0 | 1}]

       [-object_type {Wire Via}]

       [-from_pin <pin_name> -to_pin <pin_name>]

       Selects  wires  and  vias using the specified parameters. The wires are
       updated by subsequent wire editing commands.

Parameters
       -help  Prints the usage of the command. For a detailed  description  of
              the command, use the man command:

              man editSelect

       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies  the  coordinates  for  the  area from which to select
              wires and vias.

              Default: Entire area

              <x1>: Specifies the lower left x coordinate.

              <y1>: Specifies the lower left y coordinate.

              <x2>: Specifies the upper right x coordinate.

              y2: Specifies the upper right y coordinate.

       -direction {H | V | 45 | 135}
              Specifies the orientation of the wires to be selected.

              Default: If you do not specify  this  parameter,  selects  wires
              with any orientation.

              H: Specifies that horizontal wires are to be selected.

              V: Specifies that vertical wires are to be selected.

              45: Specifies that 45-degree wires are to be selected.

              135: Specifies that 135-degree wires are to be selected.

       -floating_via
              Specifies  that only floating vias are to be selected. A via, or
              a stack of vias, is floating, if it is not connected to  another
              object,  wire,  pin,  or  via, on either its top or bottom metal
              layer or on both these layers.

       -from_pin <pin_name>
              Specifies the name of the starting pin of the  wire  to  be  se-
              lected.

              The starting pin you specify should be connected to the same net
              as  the  ending  pin  specified with -to_pin. If they connect to
              different nets, the tool reports an error. In addition, the from
              and to pins you specify should be connected to the same wire.

              PG pins are also supported.

              Note: Selection of wires between  specified  pins  is  supported
              only for signal and clock nets.

       -layer <list_of_layers>
              Specifies  the  layers from which to select wires and vias. This
              option supports backside and Through Silicon Via (TSV) layers as
              well.

              If you are specifying multiple layers, enclose them in braces.

              Default: If you do not specify this parameter, selects wires and
              vias on all layers.

       -nets <net>*
              Specifies the net names from which to select wires and vias.

              You can use wildcard values in this field. For example,  if  you
              specify V*, selects wires/vias from nets VDD and VSS.

       -object_type {Wire Via}
              Specifies  whether  wires or vias or both should be selected. If
              the parameter is not specified, only wires are selected.

              Default: Wire

       -physical_pin_only
              Specifies that physical pins are to be selected. By default, ed-
              itSelect does not select physical pins.

              You can use the -physical_pin_only parameter along  with  -area,
              -layer,  or  -nets  to select the physical pins in the specified
              area, layer, or net, respectively.

       -regular_wire_with_drc
              Selects regular wires with violation  markers.  Clock  nets  are
              also selected.

       -shape {RING STRIPE FOLLOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE PADRING BLOCK-
       RING FILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC DRCFILL None}
              Specifies  the  shapes of the wires and vias to be selected. Use
              all upper-case letters for the shapes. If you  specify  multiple
              shapes,  enclose the list of shapes in braces. For shape defini-
              tions, see Shapes, in the "DEF Syntax" chapter  of  the  LEF/DEF
              Language Reference.

              Default: If you do not specify this parameter, selects wires and
              vias of all shapes.

       -shield
              Selects  the wires and vias of the nets specified with the -nets
              parameter, along with the wires and vias shielding the specified
              nets.

              Note: This parameter cannot be used with -shield_only.

       -shield_only
              Selects only the shield wires associated with the nets specified
              using the -nets parameter. The signal nets  being  shielded  are
              not selected.

              Note: This parameter cannot be used with -shield.

       -status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN}
              Specifies  the  status of wires and vias to be selected. Use all
              upper-case letters for the status. If you specify more than  one
              status, enclose the status list in braces.

              Note: If you select -type Special -status NOSHIELD or -type Sig-
              nal -status SHIELD the software generates an error message.

       -subclass <sublass_name>
              Specifies  the  subclass  name  of  the wires and vias to be se-
              lected. Use this parameter if you want to select wires  or  vias
              belonging  to  a  specific  subclass. Here, <subclass_name> is a
              user-defined attribute that has been  previously  defined  using
              the  -uda parameter of the addSplitPowerVia, addRing, addStripe,
              or sroute command.

              For wires, use this parameter if you want to  select  or  delete
              rings, stripes, or other wires belonging to a specific subclass.
              Only special wire is supported by this option.

              Note: You can use wildcards in <subclass_name>.

       -to_pin <pin_name>
              Specifies the name of the ending pin of the wire to be selected.

              The  ending  pin you specify should be connected to the same net
              as the starting pin specified with -from_pin. If they connect to
              different nets, the tool reports an error. In addition, the from
              and to pins you specify should be connected to the same wire. If
              there there are more than one wire or via between the  specified
              starting  and ending pins, the command is not able to select the
              wire path and returns an error.

              PG pins are also supported.

              The -from_pin and -to_pin parameters are  compatible  with  only
              the -direction, -layer, -object_type, and -status options of the
              editSelect  command.  If  you use -from_pin and -to_pin with any
              other editSelect parameters, the tool returns an error.

              Note: Selection of wires between  specified  pins  is  supported
              only for signal and clock nets.

       -type {Regular Special Patch}
              Specifies  whether  to  select  regular  wires and vias, special
              wires and vias, or patch wires.

              Note: If you specify Regular, you must omit the -shapes  parame-
              ter or specify -shapes None.

       -use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}
              Specifies  whether to select only CLOCK wires/vias, POWER wires,
              or SIGNAL wires.

       -via_cell <cell_name_list>
              Specifies the via cells of the vias to be selected. You can  use
              wildcards while specifying via cell names. If you are specifying
              multiple cell names, enclose them in braces.

       -with_edit_flag {0 | 1}
              Selects all modified wires and vias, that is wires and vias with
              value 1 for the isEdit property on the net.

              Notes

              * As  the  isEdit  property  is  added on the whole net, all the
                wires and vias on the net with isEdit value set to 1  will  be
                selected.

              * The  isEdit  property is used to flag nets with modified wires
                and vias. This is useful when evaluating how many objects need
                to be modified for fixing DRC  violations  and  then  deciding
                whether to fix the violations manually or through ECO routing.
                The   isEdit   property   is   controlled  through  the  -cre-
                ate_is_edit_flag parameter of setEditMode.  By  default,  this
                parameter  is set to 0. If you set the value of this parameter
                to 1, the isEdit property is set to 1 for nets  with  modified
                wires or vias.

Examples
              * The  following  command  selects  all  wires on the METAL1 and
                METAL2 layers:

                editSelect -layer {METAL1 METAL2}

              * The following command selects all vias on the cut layer VIA12:

                editSelect -layer VIA12 -object_type Via

              * The following command selects all vias on the cut layers VIA12
                and VIA23:

                editSelect -layer {VIA12 VIA23} -object_type Via

              * The following command selects all  wires  on  the  METAL1  and
                METAL2 layers and vias on the cut layer VIA12:

                editSelect  -layer  {METAL1  METAL2  VIA12} -object_type {Wire
                Via}

              * The following command selects all horizontal fillwires on  the
                METAL1 layer:

                editSelect -layer METAL1 -direction H -shape FILLWIRE

              * The  following  command  selects  VDD  STRIPEs  with  subclass
                "stripe_A":

                editSelect -nets VDD -shape  STRIPE  -type  Special  -subclass
                stripe_A

              * The following command selects all vias of shape FOLLOWPIN with
                names that match the pattern tapcellvia_VIA1_RUL*:

                editSelect  -shape  FOLLOWPIN  -via_cell  tapcellvia_VIA1_RUL*
                -object_type Via

              * The following command selects all the modified wires and vias:

                editSelect -with_edit_flag 1 -object_type {Wire Via}

              * The following command selects the complete  wire  between  the
                specified from and to pins:

                editSelect -from_pin C/A -to_pin A/A

                The selected wire is depicted in red in the diagram below:

              * The following command selects only the wire segments on the M2
                layer between the specified from and to pins:

                editSelect -from_pin C/A -to_pin A/A -layer M2

                The  selected wire segments are depicted in red in the diagram
                below:

              * The following command only the vertical wire segments  between
                the specified from and to pins:

                editSelect -from_pin C/A -to_pin A/A -direction V

                The  selected  wire  segment is depicted in red in the diagram
                below:

              * Consider the example below:

                * The following command selects all nets that have  DRC  mark-
                  ers:

                  editSelect -regular_wire_with_drc

                * The  following  command  selects wires with DRC markers from
                  only Net B:

                  editSelect -nets B -regular_wire_with_drc

                * The following command selects only  routed  wires  with  DRC
                  markers from Net B:

                  editSelect -nets B -regular_wire_with_drc -status ROUTED

              * The  following set of commands select and delete nets with DRC
                markers while excluding clock nets:

                editSelect -regular_wire_with_drc

                editDeselect -use CLOCK

                editDelete -selected

